    "slides": [
        {
            "id": "s4_1",
            "type": "text",
            "title": "What is Vectorization? ⚡",
            "content": "Vectorization means that operations are applied to each element of a vector automatically, without needing explicit loops. This makes R code concise and fast.\n\n```r\nx <- c(1, 2, 3)\nx + 1        # 2 3 4\nx * 2        # 2 4 6\nsqrt(x)      # 1.00 1.41 1.73\n```\n\nMost basic functions in R are vectorized."
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_2",
            "type": "code",
            "title": "Vectorized Arithmetic",
            "content": "See vectorization in action:",
            "codeSnippet": "x <- 1:5\nprint(x + 10)\nprint(x * 3)\nprint(x^2)\nprint(sin(x))",
            "codeLanguage": "r",
            "canRunCode": true
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_3",
            "type": "quiz",
            "title": "Vectorization Quiz 🧠",
            "content": "",
            "quizData": {
                "id": "q4_1",
                "type": "multiple_choice",
                "question": "What is the result of `c(1,2,3) + c(4,5,6)`?",
                "options": [
                    {
                        "id": "opt1",
                        "text": "c(1,2,3,4,5,6)",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt2",
                        "text": "c(5,7,9)",
                        "isCorrect": true
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt3",
                        "text": "c(4,10,18)",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt4",
                        "text": "Error",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    }
                ],
                "explanation": "Vectors of same length are added element-wise: 1+4=5, 2+5=7, 3+6=9.",
                "xpReward": 10
            }
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_4",
            "type": "text",
            "title": "Recycling Rule 🔄",
            "content": "When vectors are of different lengths, R **recycles** the shorter one to match the longer.\n\n```r\nc(1,2,3,4) + c(10,20)   # 1+10=11, 2+20=22, 3+10=13, 4+20=24\n```\n\nA warning is issued if the longer length is not a multiple of the shorter."
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_5",
            "type": "code",
            "title": "Recycling Examples",
            "content": "Try these recycling examples:",
            "codeSnippet": "print(1:6 + 1:2)\nprint(1:6 + 1:3)\nprint(matrix(1:4, nrow=2) + c(10,20))  # works column-wise",
            "codeLanguage": "r",
            "canRunCode": true
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_6",
            "type": "quiz",
            "title": "Recycling Quiz 🧠",
            "content": "",
            "quizData": {
                "id": "q4_2",
                "type": "multiple_choice",
                "question": "What is the result of `c(1,2,3,4) + c(10,20,30)`?",
                "options": [
                    {
                        "id": "opt1",
                        "text": "11 22 33 14",
                        "isCorrect": true
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt2",
                        "text": "11 22 33 44",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt3",
                        "text": "11 22 33 34",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt4",
                        "text": "Error",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    }
                ],
                "explanation": "c(10,20,30) is recycled to c(10,20,30,10) to match length 4, so 1+10=11, 2+20=22, 3+30=33, 4+10=14.",
                "xpReward": 10
            }
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_7",
            "type": "text",
            "title": "Logical Vectorization",
            "content": "Logical operations are also vectorized:\n\n```r\nx <- 1:5\nx > 3        # FALSE FALSE FALSE TRUE TRUE\nx[x > 3]     # 4 5\n```\n\nYou can combine conditions with `&` (AND) and `|` (OR):\n\n```r\nx[(x > 2) & (x < 5)]  # 3 4\n```"
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_8",
            "type": "code",
            "title": "Logical Vectorization",
            "content": "Run these logical operations:",
            "codeSnippet": "x <- c(5, -2, 8, 0, 3)\nprint(x > 0)\nprint(x[x > 0])\nprint(x[(x > 0) & (x < 5)])",
            "codeLanguage": "r",
            "canRunCode": true
        },
        {
            "id": "s4_9",
            "type": "tip",
            "title": "Pro Tip 🚀",
            "content": "Many functions like `ifelse()` are vectorized versions of if-else:\n\n```r\nifelse(x > 0, \"positive\", \"non-positive\")\n```"
        }
    ]
}